"haec utraque insuper bipedalibus trabibus immissis, quantum eorum tignorum iunctura distabat, BINIS UTRIMQUE fibulis ab extrema parte distinebantur;  quibus disclusis atque in contrariam partem revinctis, tanta erat operis firmitudo atque ea rerum natura ut, quo maior vis aquae se incitavisset, hoc artius inligata tenerentur."|"binis utrimque fibulis: with two ties on either side, i.e. at each end of the beam. The exact meaning of fibula as here used is still in dispute. Various interpretations have been suggested by different writers, as by Napoleon III, Kraner, Rheinhardt, August von Goler, and others. The interpretation adopted in these notes was probably first suggested and advocated by Colonel August von Cohausen, of the Prussian Corps of Engineers, in an elaborate and carefully prepared work on this bridge. Lieutenant F. Zimmerhaeckel, in a special treatise, recently published by Teubner, Leipzig, accepts the view of von Cohausen. Von Goler gives the same meaning to fibula, but his method of attaching it to the piles is more elaborate, requiring some nice work on the part of the joiner."

