"NOT FOUND"|"Pompeio Crasso: Caesar, Pompey, and Crassus were the members of the first triumvirate, formed for mutual help and support, which made Caesar proconsul of Gaul for five years. In April, 56 B.C., they met at Lucca and arranged that Pompey and Crassus should be consuls for the next year, and that Caesar***s proconsulship should be extended to ten years."

"NOT FOUND"|"As the engagement with the Helvetii is the first regular battle described in the Commentaries, it may be interesting to the learner to trace the general course of the action. For two weeks Caesar had been following the Helvetii, with an interval of five miles between the head of his column and the rearguard of the enemy. One favorable opportunity for giving battle had been lost, through the mistake of Considius, as described in chapter 22."

